>   Jay - Although many (most) manufacturers advertise 
>	17" monitors as supporting 1280 by 1024, what
>	they leave unsaid is that the image quality will
>	be very marginal. Some of the reasons:
>	1. The actual spot size on a 0.28 mm pitch
>	     tube is about 0.3 mm (at the 1/2 power point).
>	     The (theoretical) pixel size one is trying to
>	     display is typically the width (300 mm) 
>	     divided by 1280 = 0.23 mm. Thus adjacent
>	     pixels will tend to "run together". 
>
>	     However, this is mostly only an issue with
>	     continuous graphics images. White characters 
>	     on black background suffer from the other
>	     issues (below).
>
>	2. Focus of the spot over the face of the tube is
>	    often not optimised, and in some cases may
>	    be impossible to optimise. More costly monitors
>	    may use dynamic focus circuitry as a help, but
>	    the adjustment still relys on human judgement
>	    (There's no reliable way to measure focus). 
>	    There are also focus degradation effects from
>	    the deflection yoke which may be sorted out
>	    on more costly displays, but are simply left
>	    alone on "low end" displays such as a Samsung.
>
>	3. Misconvergence adds it's (ugly) effect especially
>	    to displaying white characters - because the white
>	    is made up of all 3 colors. If you are able to
>	    set up to display single color characters (prefer
>	    Green), you may be able to judge the effects of
>	    misconvergence. Typical spec's for convergence
>	    are 0.3 mm within the "A" area (circle with diameter
>	    equal to height of image), and as much as 0.5 mm
>	    outside that area.
>	       Bear in mind too that typical convergence specs
>	    do *not* apply all the way to the edge of the CRT,
>	    but only out to the specified image size (typically
>	    300 mm wide by 225 mm high for a 17" tube). This
>	    means the most used area of the display (upper left)
>	    is most likely to suffer from convergence effects.
>	    Mfgr's are working to improve this situation, but it's
>	    not been an easy battle.
>
>   Unfortunately, if you *really* want to run 1280, and have good
>image quality, you'll have to spend more money - either for a
>"premium" 17", or for a "reasonable" 19" (or larger).
>
>Hope this helps at least understand the issues.
>
>	Regards,
>	   Bill Nott - Monitor Engr - Compaq
